<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: OJAI VALLEY; 
</P>
<P>
REVISED WATER PLAN IS MORE OPTIMISTIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THIA BELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Casitas Municipal Water District has drafted revisions of a five-year water 
management plan that sparked controversy when it was adopted in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
The board will take public comment on the revised Urban Water Management Plan 
through Dec. 19, when it will hold a public hearing on the plan. 
</P>
<P>
The 1985 plan was attacked by environmentalists who said it was too vague, that 
it did not do enough to prevent a water shortage and that it gave the district 
too much power over smaller water agencies inside its boundaries. 
</P>
<P>
The plan had predicted customer demands for water could outstrip the district's 
available supply before the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
The revised plan paints a rosier picture by showing a possible surplus of 
almost 5,000 acre-feet of water by 2005. The district serves the Ojai Valley 
and parts of Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
The new document outlines many conservation measures the district has 
undertaken since the board declared a water-shortage emergency in April, such 
as requiring agricultural irrigation audits and low-flow plumbing fixtures in 
remodeled dwellings. 
</P>
<P>
More conservation efforts, higher water rates and imported water from the 
California Aqueduct are calculated to provide the surplus. THIA BELL 
</P>
</TEXT>
