<HEADLINE>
<P>
PENTAGON ORDERS MILLIONS OF FRESH MEALS FOR TROOPS IN DESERT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Instead of slicing open 5-year-old plastic ration pouches, American troops on 
patrol at the front lines in Saudi Arabia soon will be able to eat meals as 
fresh as packaged, preservative-laced food can be. 
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon has placed a $260-million order for nearly 190 million entree 
side-dish packs for its basic battlefield ration in a move to preserve and 
build up dwindling supplies of the food soldiers carry into battle. 
</P>
<P>
That's about a six-month supply of food for a force of 400,000 eating three 
meals a day. 
</P>
<P>
The contracts were let this week to seven food suppliers throughout the country 
and include dishes such as spaghetti with meat sauce, ham slices, chicken a la 
king, omelets with ham, chicken stew and beef stew. 
</P>
<P>
The troops at the front have been using up meals at the rate of about 1 million 
a month, and Lorraine Netzko, a spokeswoman for the Defense Personnel Support 
Center in Philadelphia, which issued the contracts, said officials decided that 
although they had stockpiles for the event of war and had no supply concerns 
for a year, they should start building up the stockpiles again. 
</P>
<P>
Until now, the Defense Logistics Agency has been shipping out meals packaged in 
1987, 1988 and 1989. Some troops took with them meals put together in 1984 and 
1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
FOOD; FOOD DISTRIBUTION; DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE (U.S.) -- CONTRACTS; IRAQ -- 
FOREIGN RELATIONS -- KUWAIT; MILITARY CONFRONTATIONS; IRAQ -- ARMED FORCES -- 
KUWAIT; UNITED STATES -- ARMED FORCES -- PERSIAN GULF 
</P>
