<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOLIS, PATTON HOSPITALIZED AFTER 3-HORSE SPILL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB MIESZERSKI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jockeys Alex Solis, Robbie Davis and Dave Patton escaped serious injury in a 
three-horse spill during the first race Friday at Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred when Fields Of Belles, Patton's mount, broke down 
entering the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
Solis, riding Baffis Habitony, and Davis, aboard Vaunty, went down when they 
were unable to avoid the fallen horse and rider. 
</P>
<P>
Davis, who was able to walk away from the spill, was taken to Centinela 
Hospital Medical Center, where X-rays of his right arm proved negative. He was 
sent home and cleared to ride this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
Solis, who is third in the Hollywood Park rider standings behind Chris McCarron 
and Kent Desormeaux, and Patton, both suffered concussions and were to spend in 
the hospital for observation. 
</P>
<P>
Solis, who was scheduled to ride Balla Cove in today's $100,000 Affirmed 
Handicap and Formal Dinner in Sunday's $1-million Hollywood Futurity, also was 
treated for a scalp bruise. Doctors said Solis could ride if he is feeling well 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
Patton, who didn't regain consciousness until he reached the hospital, required 
stitches for a scalp cut. 
</P>
<P>
Fields Of Belles, a 3-year-old maiden filly making her second start for trainer 
Mark MacDonald, broke the cannon bone in her right foreleg and was destroyed. 
Baffis Habitony and Vaunty were not injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
