<P>
MARINES TO DISCHARGE CONSCIENTIOUS OBJECTOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AMY WALLACE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Hawaii-based Marine, who in August became the first to refuse deployment to 
the Middle East, has been transferred to Camp Pendleton to be processed for 
release from active duty, the Marine Corps announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Jeffrey A. Paterson, a 22-year-old corporal, was granted an administrative 
discharge Wednesday. He had applied for conscientious-objector status. He was 
transferred Thursday to Camp Pendleton to begin at least three days of 
processing, said Staff Sgt. Vicki Turney, a Camp Pendleton spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
Paterson will not be allowed interviews with the media until his processing is 
complete, Turney said. AMY WALLACE 
</P>
